   =20
      Derivatives structuring
   =20
 =20

Disclosure! I used to sell customized derivatives at Goldman Sachs Group In=
c. There are roughly four steps in pricing a complex derivative to show to =
a client:
=09You need a pricing model for that=C2=A0type of derivative. This will be =
built by quants and will live in the bank=E2=80=99s systems (or on Bloomber=
g), ready to be applied to particular cases; you pick the model and then fi=
ll in the terms of the trade.=09You need to get market data (prices, volati=
lities, interest rates, etc.) to input into the model. This data will=C2=A0=
be ingested and will also live on the bank=E2=80=99s systems (or on Bloombe=
rg), ready to be used by the model.=C2=A0=09You might need to adjust the ma=
rket data, somewhat subjectively, to account for the size and risk and liqu=
idity and terms of your particular trade. If your market data feed says tha=
t the implied volatility of a six-month 100-share call option is 35%, but y=
ou are selling a five-year option on 10 million shares, you might not want =
to use 35%.=09Then the model will give you a price, and you will look at it=
 and ask yourself =E2=80=9Chow much more can I charge the client for this t=
rade?=E2=80=9D If the trade is fairly standard and the client is an aggress=
ive hedge fund with its own model who is bidding out the trade to six banks=
 and will call your boss to scream at her if your price is wide, you will q=
uote pretty much what the model says is fair value. If the trade is unique =
and the client is an   assistant treasurer at a sleepy corporate client who=
 is grateful to you for taking him out to an occasional steak dinner, you w=
ill add like 2% edge to the model price.=C2=A0This is the most important pa=
rt of the job.


Oh, I kid, probably programming the model (Step 1) is the most important pa=
rt; if you get that wrong then you have huge systemic problems. But the qua=
nts do that. At the level of derivatives sales, nudging the price up to wha=
t the client is willing to pay is what earns you your bonus.
  [1]

Anyway Steps 1 and 2 are fairly deterministic; there are broadly accepted w=
ays to price derivatives and to obtain and clean market data.
  [2]
 Step 3 requires a certain intuitive=C2=A0feel=C2=A0for markets, and for ri=
sk, and for the firm=E2=80=99s positions and risk appetite. That=C2=A0feel =
typically comes from thoughtful experience in the markets, but could it als=
o come from, like, a regression? Sure? This pattern recognition seems=C2=A0=
like the sort of thing an artificial intelligence could get good at.
Step 4 requires a certain intuitive feel=C2=A0for the client. Again, typica=
lly from experience with clients, but could a robot figure out =E2=80=9Csho=
w tight prices to big hedge funds and wide prices to sleepy corporate treas=
urers=E2=80=9D? Sure? Could the robot take the assistant treasurers out to =
the steak dinners? You probably still need salespeople for something.
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s William Shaw   reports on Goldman=E2=80=99s current pla=
ns for selling customized derivatives:

Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is expanding its use of a technology that leverage=
s artificial intelligence in the hopes that it will make it easier for clie=
nts to plan complex derivatives trades.
After already using the software to shake up the worlds of equities and for=
eign exchange options, the firm in recent weeks began allowing clients to u=
se its visual structuring product for credit derivatives. It=E2=80=99s aimi=
ng to offer the service for rates trading in the first half of next year, C=
hris Churchman, who runs Goldman=E2=80=99s digital trading platform Marquee=
, said in an interview.
The product, which Goldman began offering last year, helps institutional cl=
ients with price discovery and trading ideas. It also assesses the risks of=
 a given trade and can gauge the chances that the trade will pay off.
To do so, the offering uses neural networks, which learn through trial and =
error like a human brain, as well as natural language processing, which dec=
iphers vast troves of speech and text, to price some complex trades. =E2=80=
=A6
For instance, if a client is interested in trading a particular asset, the =
system can quickly analyze how that asset=E2=80=99s current premium compare=
s to past periods. The system can also instantaneously price different vari=
ations of a trade, predict when it might pay off and show how that investme=
nt might behave as the prices of other assets move.

Okay. I guess my question is, do the neural nets know how much to charge? L=
ike if you log on to this thing and do a ton of sophisticated modeling and =
price up a bunch of slightly different variations to minimize premium, does=
 the neural net think =E2=80=9Chuh this person is gonna fight for every bas=
is point=E2=80=9D and start showing you tighter prices? If you log on to th=
is thing and, in the natural-language input box, you type =E2=80=9Cwhat is =
derivative,=E2=80=9D does the neural net gleefully rub its little electroni=
c hands together and say =E2=80=9Cooh this is gonna make my year=E2=80=9D?
  [3]


