      SBF Stuff: Testimony
   =20
 =20

 Obviously:

Sam Bankman-Fried will take the stand to defend his actions in the lead-up =
to the collapse of his digital-asset empire, after taking a beating from fo=
rmer colleagues who painted him as the mastermind of a years-long scheme to=
 defraud customers and investors.
Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s lawyers told the judge on Wednesday that their clie=
nt will testify in his own trial when they start their defense case later t=
his week.

There are kind of two theories of criminal trials in the US:
=09The prosecution has the burden of proving that you did a crime. They put=
 on a case, and your lawyers pick holes in it, trying to create =E2=80=9Cre=
asonable doubt=E2=80=9D in the minds of jurors. The jury then goes back and=
 decides whether the prosecution has proven its case beyond a reasonable do=
ubt. If yes, you are convicted. If they are not sure, you are acquitted.=09=
The prosecution tells a story (in which you did a crime), and your lawyers =
tell a different story (in which you are innocent). The jury then goes back=
 and decides which story is more compelling. If it=E2=80=99s the prosecutio=
n story, you are convicted. If it=E2=80=99s your story, you are acquitted.

Theory 1 is=C2=A0correct, as a matter of law; that is how the law is suppos=
ed to work, and what the judge=E2=80=99s instructions to the jury will say,=
 and what happens in=C2=A0Twelve Angry Men, and how a lot of criminal defen=
se lawyers think about things.
In particular, criminal defense lawyers will be very cautious about=C2=A0te=
lling their own competing story, because they will not want the jury to com=
pare stories. As a matter of legal theory, if jurors look=C2=A0at two compe=
ting stories and say=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe=C2=A0think the prosecution is 70% lik=
ely to be right and the defense is 30% likely to be right,=E2=80=9D then=C2=
=A0they should acquit, because that is reasonable doubt. But faced directly=
 with the two stories, they might be inclined to pick the more compelling o=
ne; they might convict because the prosecution=E2=80=99s story is=C2=A0some=
what=C2=A0better than the defense=E2=80=99s. And so defense lawyers will re=
sist giving the jurors a head-to-head comparison; they will focus on holes =
in the prosecution=E2=80=99s case, so they can emphasize =E2=80=9Cthe prose=
cution=E2=80=99s story is not true beyond doubt=E2=80=9D rather than the ha=
rder =E2=80=9Cour story is better than theirs.=E2=80=9D
I have always been partial to Theory 2 anyway. People like stories! Jurors =
will be tempted to pick a flawed story from the prosecution over=C2=A0no=C2=
=A0story from the defense. They are sitting in the courtroom, you are sitti=
ng at the defendant=E2=80=99s table, they are going to assume you did somet=
hing wrong. You have to give them an innocent explanation of how you came t=
o be there. You have to give them something to feel good about if they are =
going to acquit.
This is just idle musing, and I am probably wrong in the general case. But =
this case is easy! The prosecutors have basically all of Sam Bankman-Fried=
=E2=80=99s colleagues testifying =E2=80=9Cwe did tons of crimes because Sam=
 told us to.=E2=80=9D They have the computer code for FTX, which is   strik=
ingly crime-y for computer code. Even if they didn=E2=80=99t have any of th=
at, they have the brute facts of:
=09Customers put billions of dollars=C2=A0into FTX.=09Sam Bankman-Fried spe=
nt billions of dollars on luxury real estate and political campaigns and ce=
lebrity endorsements and personal investments.=09The customer money is gone=
.

You really don=E2=80=99t need anything else for a jury to be like =E2=80=9C=
ooh yeah that story is bad=E2=80=9D! If the defense=E2=80=99s closing argum=
ent is, like, spending six hours poking holes in the witnesses=E2=80=99 tes=
timony, that doesn=E2=80=99t help! There=E2=80=99s too much of it! The jury=
 can be like =E2=80=9Csure yes the defense raised some doubts about 200 of =
the 1,000 pieces of evidence against him but, still, man, not good.=E2=80=
=9D
Meanwhile Sam Bankman-Fried   has a competing story in which the money vani=
shed through a combination of unexpected crypto market moves and innocent a=
ccounting mistakes. Is this as good a story as the prosecution=E2=80=99s st=
ory? No! Is it his only chance of winning? Obviously!

 =20
   =20
      SBF Stuff: Toward a general theory of scammers
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think SBF knowingly stole customer money,=E2=80=9D=
  said=C2=A0Michael Lewis on 60 Minutes, and =E2=80=9Che believes he is inn=
ocent.=E2=80=9D If Lewis is correct then that will probably help him testif=
y: If you=E2=80=99re going to be subjected to withering cross-examination=
=C2=A0about the crimes you did, it helps if you believe that you are innoce=
nt.
Is Lewis right? I think so! But that is, I think, the normal state for a sc=
ammer.
  [4]
=C2=A0Financial scams are in their essence about=C2=A0self-deception; you c=
an=E2=80=99t be a great scammer without being at least somewhat deluded you=
rself.
  [5]
=C2=A0Classically financial scams work along these lines:
=09There is a financial business that takes money from investors, customers=
, creditors, etc., and promises to give it back, usually with some return.=
=09The person running the business has at least some discretion over what h=
e does with the investors=E2=80=99 money. (Practical discretion =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0he has the password to the bank account =E2=80=94=C2=A0if not actual =
legal discretion.)=09He makes bets with that money, with the intention of (=
1) getting back at least enough money to pay back his investors (and any pr=
omised return) and (2) keeping any extra winnings for himself.=09
He convinces himself this is fine. He can=E2=80=99t lose! He=E2=80=99s so g=
ood at making bets, and these bets are so safe, and anyway the clients woul=
d want him to do them, and also really aren=E2=80=99t they disclosed in the=
 fine print of the clients=E2=80=99 account agreements?=C2=A0

The popular imagination of scammers, and of Bankman-Fried, is that they ste=
eple their fingers and cackle and say =E2=80=9Cnow to steal some customer m=
oney to buy mansions.=E2=80=9D But=C2=A0why would that make sense? If you a=
re Bankman-Fried and you are knowingly stealing customer money to buy Baham=
as condos, and then everything collapses, why stay in the condos to get arr=
ested? Also if you are knowingly stealing money then=C2=A0of course everyth=
ing will collapse. Stealing money with a getaway plan? Sure, right, that ha=
ppens. Stealing money and sticking around? Weird choice.
No, the way to end up in this situation is to steal money while thinking th=
at it=E2=80=99s fine, that you=E2=80=99re not stealing it at all, that you=
=E2=80=99ll make it all back and then some, that what you are doing with th=
e money (crypto altcoin arbitrage, buying politicians, buying publicity for=
 crypto and your exchange) is necessary and profitable and not even a risk,=
 that any losses are temporary blips.=C2=A0
The normal way to become a big-time scammer is to combine an unusual appeti=
te for (indeed, blindness to) risk=C2=A0with an unusual self-confidence. An=
d to add an unusually act-utilitarian=C2=A0mindset, in which you are unconc=
erned with doing things the right way or following the proper procedures, b=
ecause you=C2=A0care only about the end result.
Does that remind you of anyone? Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s whole personali=
ty was utilitarianism and risk-taking.
  [6]
 He   learned early on to take   every positive-expected-value bet, and fro=
m the start he seems to have deluded himself=C2=A0about what bets had posit=
ive expected value. The early history of his crypto trading firm, Alameda R=
esearch, involved him losing a bunch of investor money, saying =E2=80=9Cehh=
 there=E2=80=99s like an 80% chance we get it back,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0concludin=
g he could lie to customers=C2=A0about the lost money, and then in fact get=
ting it back and feeling vindicated. He had the most perfect imaginable tra=
ining for running a big financial scam.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      SBF Stuff: FTX 2.0
   =20
 =20

The description above is not=C2=A0often=C2=A0consistent with:
=09running a good legitimate business and=09making bets, with the customer =
money, that pay off.

But it is not=C2=A0in principle=C2=A0inconsistent. It=E2=80=99s just that, =
ordinarily, if you take wild risks with other people=E2=80=99s money, lie t=
o them about what you are doing, delude yourself into thinking that there=
=E2=80=99s no risk, and the bets pay out and you build a great business and=
 everyone gets their money back, we don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0call=C2=A0you a scam=
mer. We call you an unconventional visionary who moves fast and breaks thin=
gs.
  [7]
=C2=A0There is a ton of  moral luck involved in the popular and legal deter=
mination of who is a scammer and who is a maverick billionaire.
I do not pretend to understand the finances of the FTX bankruptcy estate at=
 this point,
  [8]
 but it does seem at least possible that Sam Bankman-Fried was (1) running =
a good legitimate business and (2) making bets, with customer money, that w=
ill pay off? We   talked a few weeks ago about FTX=E2=80=99s stake in Anthr=
opic, an artificial intelligence company, which has rapidly increased in va=
lue since Bankman-Fried invested, making FTX=E2=80=99s stake worth billions=
 of dollars and going some way to filling the hole in customer funds.
Also though the FTX exchange seems to have been a good enough business that=
,=C2=A0even now, somebody might pay for it. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Steven Ch=
urch reports:

FTX Trading Ltd. is considering proposals from three bidders to restart tra=
ding on what had been one of the world=E2=80=99s biggest crypto exchanges b=
efore the company sank into bankruptcy amid fraud allegations.
The company will make a decision about how to proceed by mid-December, the =
company=E2=80=99s investment banker, Kevin M. Cofsky of Perella Weinberg Pa=
rtners, said Tuesday during a court hearing in Wilmington, Delaware. FTX is=
 negotiating details of potentially binding offers with investors, Cofsky s=
aid.
Options include selling the entire exchange, including a valuable list of m=
ore than 9 million customers, or bringing in a partner to help restart the =
exchange, Cofsky told US Bankruptcy Judge John Dorsey. FTX is also mulling =
a reboot of the trading platform on its own, he said. =E2=80=A6
FTX and its main creditor groups have tentatively settled some of the most =
difficult disputes in the case, which will allow the company to file a deta=
iled payout plan in December, company attorney Andrew Dietderich said in co=
urt.
In bankruptcy, such plans typically give creditors an estimate =E2=80=94 ex=
pressed as a percentage =E2=80=94 of how much they can expect to recover. F=
TX, however, doesn=E2=80=99t currently know what customers will get back, D=
ietderich said. The recovery percentage will in part depend on how much val=
ue FTX can get from a potential sale, or reboot, of the exchange.

Of course, last November, this is exactly   what Bankman-Fried himself was =
pitching: He had a pot of weird assets (including Anthropic) and an exchang=
e with some franchise value, and he was trying to sell them as a package=C2=
=A0for at least a penny more than the customer deposits. He almost got Bina=
nce to buy, but then Binance did some more due diligence,  noticed the miss=
ing customer money, was like =E2=80=9Chmm we don=E2=80=99t want to touch th=
at=E2=80=9D and backed out.=C2=A0
Just the=C2=A0timing=C2=A0of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s moral luck is fascinat=
ing. If he had managed to find a buyer then, look, this would all still be=
=C2=A0bad, and probably=C2=A0fraud, and he might even get in=C2=A0trouble. =
(His venture capitalist investors, for instance, would have complaints if B=
inance had actually bought FTX for $0.) But it would probably be, relativel=
y speaking, pretty minor trouble. If you lose $8 billion of customer deposi=
ts you get in very bad trouble. Unless you find them again=C2=A0before=C2=
=A0you get arrested! After is no good.
It=E2=80=99s not all luck, though. It is plausible that, now that FTX=E2=80=
=99s bankruptcy estate is shopping the exchange to buyers, it has a positiv=
e value, but when Bankman-Fried was shopping it last year it had a large ne=
gative value,=C2=A0because Bankman-Fried was running it then and he=E2=80=
=99s not now. An exchange that operates pretty well but that is run by a gu=
y who is stealing all the money really is worth less, as a going concern, t=
han the shell of that exchange after he=E2=80=99s gone.

