   =20
      SBF Stuff: Shadow trading?
   =20
 =20

There is no news hook here =E2=80=94=C2=A0this is a decades-old academic pa=
per=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s news to me: Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=
=80=99s father, Joseph Bankman, wrote a paper on shadow trading in 2001.=C2=
=A0Here is =E2=80=9CSubstitutes for Insider Trading,=E2=80=9D by Bankman an=
d Ian Ayres:
When insider trading prohibitions limit the ability of insiders (or of a co=
rporation itself) to use material non-public information to trade a particu=
lar firm=E2=80=99s stock, there may be incentive to use the information to =
trade instead on the stock of that firm=E2=80=99s rivals, suppliers, custom=
ers, or the manufacturers of complementary products. We refer to this form =
of trading as trading in stock substitutes. Stock substitute trading by a f=
irm is legal. In many circumstance, substitute trading by employees is also=
 legal. Trading in stock substitutes may be quite profitable, and there is =
anecdotal evidence that employees often engage in such trading. Our analysi=
s suggests that substitute trading is less socially desirable than traditio=
nal insider trading. We recommend a set of disclosure rules designed to cla=
rify existing law and provide information on the extent of stock substitute=
 trading. We also discuss possible changes in the law that might limit inef=
ficient trading in stock substitutes.
We have   talked before about   shadow trading, as this form of substitute =
trading is now often called. I have to say, =E2=80=9Clegal in many circumst=
ances=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cquite profitable=E2=80=9D is much better than w=
hat Bankman-Fried eventually did get up to.

 =20
   =20
      Twitter debt
   =20
 =20

Could  be worse:

The banks that financed Elon Musk's $44 billion purchase of Twitter are sti=
ll struggling a year later to contain the damage to their balance sheets.
The banks currently expect to take a hit of at least 15%, or roughly $2 bil=
lion, when they sell the debt, people familiar with the matter said. That w=
ould mean hundreds of millions in losses for those holding the largest piec=
es, which include Morgan Stanley, Bank of America, Barclays and MUFG. BNP P=
aribas, Soci=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale and Mizuho were also involved.
After holding the debt for a year -- an eternity in the corporate-finance w=
orld -- the banks, which had hoped they could sell it by Labor Day, have re=
cently begun preparations to try to unload at least some of it, the people =
said.

Around the deal=E2=80=99s closing there was talk of banks getting bids at 5=
0 cents on the dollar, so 85 would be pretty good? One purpose of installin=
g Linda Yaccarino as the chief executive officer of Twitter (now called X) =
is that she can have basically normal conversations with investors as the b=
anks try to sell the debt; investors will say things like =E2=80=9Chow=E2=
=80=99s business?=E2=80=9D and she will say things like =E2=80=9Coh good, g=
ood, advertisers coming back, really good.=E2=80=9D As opposed to sending E=
lon Musk to those meetings and having him get bored and start trouble. =E2=
=80=9CHow=E2=80=99s business,=E2=80=9D investors would ask, and he=E2=80=99=
d be like =E2=80=9Cyou know what I=E2=80=99ve decided that debt isn=E2=80=
=99t real=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99d never get 85 cents on the dollar.

