<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Derivatives structuring</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Disclosure! I used to sell customized derivati=
ves at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. There are roughly four steps in pricing a c=
omplex derivative to show to a client:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You need a pricing model for that=C2=
=A0type of derivative. This will be built by quants and will live in the ba=
nk=E2=80=99s systems (or on Bloomberg), ready to be applied to particular c=
ases; you pick the model and then fill in the terms of the trade.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You need to get market data (prices, volati=
lities, interest rates, etc.) to input into the model. This data will=C2=A0=
be ingested and will also live on the bank=E2=80=99s systems (or on Bloombe=
rg), ready to be used by the model.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">You might need to adjust the market data, somewhat subjectively, to=
 account for the size and risk and liquidity and terms of your particular t=
rade. If your market data feed says that the implied volatility of a six-mo=
nth 100-share call option is 35%, but you are selling a five-year option on=
 10 million shares, you might not want to use 35%.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">Then the model will give you a price, and you will look at=
 it and ask yourself =E2=80=9Chow much more can I charge the client for thi=
s trade?=E2=80=9D If the trade is fairly standard and the client is an aggr=
essive hedge fund with its own model who is bidding out the trade to six ba=
nks and will call your boss to scream at her if your price is wide, you wil=
l quote pretty much what the model says is fair value. If the trade is uniq=
ue and the client is an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/33142177.286418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMTIvZnR4LWhhZC1tYW55LWJhZC1zcHJlYWRzaGVldHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAy=
NTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMxMDI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
fdb5c430" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  assistant treasurer at a sleepy corporate client</a> wh=
o is grateful to you for taking him out to an occasional steak dinner, you =
will add like 2% edge to the model price.=C2=A0<em>This is the most importa=
nt part of the job.</em>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, I kid, probably programming the model (Ste=
p 1) is the most important part; if you get that wrong then you have huge s=
ystemic problems. But the quants do that. At the level of derivatives sales=
, nudging the price up to what the client is willing to pay is what earns y=
ou your bonus.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Steps 1 and 2 are fairly deterministic;=
 there are broadly accepted ways to price derivatives and to obtain and cle=
an market data.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Step 3 requires a certain intuitive=C2=A0<em>feel=C2=A0</em>for market=
s, and for risk, and for the firm=E2=80=99s positions and risk appetite. Th=
at=C2=A0feel typically comes from thoughtful experience in the markets, but=
 could it also come from, like, a regression? Sure? This pattern recognitio=
n seems=C2=A0like the sort of thing an artificial intelligence could get go=
od at.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Step 4 requires a certain intuitive feel=C2=A0=
for the client. Again, typically from experience with clients, but could a =
robot figure out =E2=80=9Cshow tight prices to big hedge funds and wide pri=
ces to sleepy corporate treasurers=E2=80=9D? Sure? Could the robot take the=
 assistant treasurers out to the steak dinners? You probably still need sal=
espeople for something.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s William Shaw <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33142177.286418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMjUvZ29sZG1hbi1ncy13YW50cy=
10by1tYWtlLWl0LWVhc2llci10by1wbGFuLWNvbXBsZXgtZGVyaXZhdGl2ZXMtdHJhZGVzP2Ntc=
GlkPUJCRDEwMjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdz=
bGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTAyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBcc8c01b0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  reports on Goldman=E2=80=99s current plans=
</a> for selling customized derivatives:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is expanding its use =
of a technology that leverages artificial intelligence in the hopes that it=
 will make it easier for clients to plan complex derivatives trades.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After already using the software to shake up t=
he worlds of equities and foreign exchange options, the firm in recent week=
s began allowing clients to use its visual structuring product for credit d=
erivatives. It=E2=80=99s aiming to offer the service for rates trading in t=
he first half of next year, Chris Churchman, who runs Goldman=E2=80=99s dig=
ital trading platform Marquee, said in an interview.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The product, which Goldman began offering last=
 year, helps institutional clients with price discovery and trading ideas. =
It also assesses the risks of a given trade and can gauge the chances that =
the trade will pay off.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To do so, the offering uses neural networks, w=
hich learn through trial and error like a human brain, as well as natural l=
anguage processing, which deciphers vast troves of speech and text, to pric=
e some complex trades. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance, if a client is interested in tra=
ding a particular asset, the system can quickly analyze how that asset=E2=
=80=99s current premium compares to past periods. The system can also insta=
ntaneously price different variations of a trade, predict when it might pay=
 off and show how that investment might behave as the prices of other asset=
s move.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay. I guess my question is, do the neural ne=
ts know how much to charge? Like if you log on to this thing and do a ton o=
f sophisticated modeling and price up a bunch of slightly different variati=
ons to minimize premium, does the neural net think =E2=80=9Chuh this person=
 is gonna fight for every basis point=E2=80=9D and start showing you tighte=
r prices? If you log on to this thing and, in the natural-language input bo=
x, you type =E2=80=9Cwhat is derivative,=E2=80=9D does the neural net gleef=
ully rub its little electronic hands together and say =E2=80=9Cooh this is =
gonna make my year=E2=80=9D?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
