<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SBF Stuff: Testimony</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/33142177.286418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMjUvc2JmLXRvLXRlc3RpZnktaW4tZnJhdWQtdHJpYWwtYWZ0ZXItb25zbGF=
1Z2h0LWZyb20taW5uZXItY2lyY2xlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZW=
RpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMTAyNSZ1dG1fY2Ftc=
GFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5282e4d0" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Obviously=
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sam Bankman-Fried will take the stand to defen=
d his actions in the lead-up to the collapse of his digital-asset empire, a=
fter taking a beating from former colleagues who painted him as the masterm=
ind of a years-long scheme to defraud customers and investors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s lawyers told the judge=
 on Wednesday that their client will testify in his own trial when they sta=
rt their defense case later this week.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are kind of two theories of criminal tri=
als in the US:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The prosecution has the burden of pro=
ving that you did a crime. They put on a case, and your lawyers pick holes =
in it, trying to create =E2=80=9Creasonable doubt=E2=80=9D in the minds of =
jurors. The jury then goes back and decides whether the prosecution has pro=
ven its case beyond a reasonable doubt. If yes, you are convicted. If they =
are not sure, you are acquitted.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">T=
he prosecution tells a story (in which you did a crime), and your lawyers t=
ell a different story (in which you are innocent). The jury then goes back =
and decides which story is more compelling. If it=E2=80=99s the prosecution=
 story, you are convicted. If it=E2=80=99s your story, you are acquitted.</=
li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Theory 1 is=C2=A0<em>correct</em>, as a matter=
 of law; that is how the law is supposed to work, and what the judge=E2=80=
=99s instructions to the jury will say, and what happens in=C2=A0<em><a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33142177.286418/aHR0cHM6=
Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvMTJfQW5ncnlfTWVuXygxOTU3X2ZpbG0p/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBc584ed97" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">Twelve Angry Men</a></em>, and how a lot o=
f criminal defense lawyers think about things.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In particular, criminal defense lawyers will b=
e very cautious about=C2=A0telling their own competing story, because they =
<em>will not want the jury to compare stories</em>. As a matter of legal th=
eory, if jurors look=C2=A0at two competing stories and say=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe=
=C2=A0think the prosecution is 70% likely to be right and the defense is 30=
% likely to be right,=E2=80=9D then=C2=A0<em>they should acquit</em>, becau=
se that is reasonable doubt. But faced directly with the two stories, they =
might be inclined to pick the more compelling one; they might convict becau=
se the prosecution=E2=80=99s story is=C2=A0<em>somewhat=C2=A0</em>better th=
an the defense=E2=80=99s. And so defense lawyers will resist giving the jur=
ors a head-to-head comparison; they will focus on holes in the prosecution=
=E2=80=99s case, so they can emphasize =E2=80=9Cthe prosecution=E2=80=99s s=
tory is not true beyond doubt=E2=80=9D rather than the harder =E2=80=9Cour =
story is better than theirs.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have always been partial to Theory 2 anyway.=
 People like stories! Jurors will be tempted to pick a flawed story from th=
e prosecution over=C2=A0<em>no=C2=A0</em>story from the defense. They are s=
itting in the courtroom, you are sitting at the defendant=E2=80=99s table, =
they are going to assume you did something wrong. You have to give them an =
innocent explanation of how you came to be there. You have to give them som=
ething to feel good about if they are going to acquit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is just idle musing, and I am probably wr=
ong in the general case. But this case is easy! The prosecutors have basica=
lly all of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s colleagues testifying =E2=80=9Cwe di=
d tons of crimes because Sam told us to.=E2=80=9D They have the computer co=
de for FTX, which is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/33142177.286418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
