;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Financial scams are in their essence about=C2=A0<em>self-</em>dec=
eption; you can=E2=80=99t be a great scammer without being at least somewha=
t deluded yourself.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Classically financial scams work along these lines:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is a financial business that tak=
es money from investors, customers, creditors, etc., and promises to give i=
t back, usually with some return.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
The person running the business has at least some discretion over what he d=
oes with the investors=E2=80=99 money. (Practical discretion =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0he has the password to the bank account =E2=80=94=C2=A0if not actual leg=
al discretion.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He makes bets with=
 that money, with the intention of (1) getting back at least enough money t=
o pay back his investors (and any promised return) and (2) keeping any extr=
a winnings for himself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>He convinces himself this is fine</em>. He can=E2=80=99t lose! He=E2=80=
=99s so good at making bets, and these bets are so safe, and anyway the cli=
ents would want him to do them, and also really aren=E2=80=99t they disclos=
ed in the fine print of the clients=E2=80=99 account agreements?=C2=A0</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The popular imagination of scammers, and of Ba=
nkman-Fried, is that they steeple their fingers and cackle and say =E2=80=
=9Cnow to steal some customer money to buy mansions.=E2=80=9D But=C2=A0why =
would that make sense? If you are Bankman-Fried and you are knowingly steal=
ing customer money to buy Bahamas condos, and then everything collapses, wh=
y stay in the condos to get arrested? Also if you are knowingly stealing mo=
ney then=C2=A0<em>of course everything will collapse</em>. Stealing money w=
ith a getaway plan? Sure, right, that happens. Stealing money and sticking =
around? Weird choice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No, the way to end up in this situation is to =
steal money while thinking that it=E2=80=99s fine, that you=E2=80=99re not =
stealing it at all, that you=E2=80=99ll make it all back and then some, tha=
t what you are doing with the money (crypto altcoin arbitrage, buying polit=
icians, buying publicity for crypto and your exchange) is necessary and pro=
fitable and not even a risk, that any losses are temporary blips.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The normal way to become a big-time scammer is=
 to combine an unusual appetite for (indeed, blindness to) risk=C2=A0with a=
n unusual self-confidence. And to add an unusually act-utilitarian=C2=A0min=
dset, in which you are unconcerned with doing things the right way or follo=
wing the proper procedures, because you=C2=A0care only about the end result=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Does that remind you of anyone? Sam Bankman-Fr=
ied=E2=80=99s whole personality was utilitarianism and risk-taking.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
